<TEXT>
in the coalmining town of nalaikh 
lhagvadorj the driver was expressing doubt that preparations for 
sundays elections were fair suddenly an angry woman strode up 
and began berating him 
she says that we are agitating against the communist party 
lhagvadorj said after the woman fell into sullen silence she is 
a member 
asked if he was afraid the driver looked serious 
she will certainly tell the officials about this he said 
adding that it could get him in trouble 
in mongolias capital of ulan bator communist party leaders say 
they want the countrys first multiparty elections to be fair they 
say they are willing to share power with opposition parties 
demanding human rights and a market economy and express support 
for those goals 
but the scene in nalaikh just outside ulan bator dramatized a 
key obstacle local communists unwilling to give up the absolute 
power the party held for nearly seven decades 
this spring popular demonstrations in ulan bator inspired by 
the anticommunist revolution in eastern europe forced the 
communists formally known as the mongolian peoples revolutionary 
party to overhaul their leadership legalize opposition parties 
and reduce controls on religion and the media 
but lhagvadorj and many opposition supporters said friday the 
communists still controlled too many aspects of the election 
process 
the first round of balloting held last sunday knocked out 
about onethird of the fledgling oppositions candidates for the 
430seat legislature the great peoples hural 
the final round of voting comes sunday 
lhagvadorj who like most mongolians uses only one name said 
candidates were supposed to be nominated by the people this time 
but he said the first he heard of nominations was when officials 
brought the final list around 
other nalaikh residents nodded in agreement 
the nominees are mostly the chiefs top officials not from 
among the workers said munhkjargal a worker 
but we cannot do anything said a young man we have to 
give our vote to one of them 
with the opposition still in the running for only about 100 
great hurals seats the communists are guaranteed victory but the 
nalaikh voters comments indicate that a communist victory cannot 
be interpreted as a rejection of reform 
a better barometer may be the party popularity poll on sundays 
ballot voters are to mark which party they support in addition to 
choosing a candidate who may or may not be from that party 
the results will be used to allocate seats in the new small 
hural a 53seat body that will meet in between the great hurals 
annual sessions it will draft and pass legislation which the 
great hural can overturn and handle daytoday matters 
opposition leaders say they believe they could capture a 
majority in the small hural 
all the parties seemed uncomfortable with the messiness of 
pluralistic politics there were few election posters and no 
debates many candidates simply sponsored free concerts or movies 
in their district to gain name recognition 
although all parties say they want greater personal freedoms 
rule of law less central planning and other reforms they differ 
widely in the pace and boldness of such moves 
