<TEXT>
a department of health and human services 
advisory panel recommended removing social security from the 
calculation of deficit reduction targets to focus public attention 
on the ballooning deficit 
the advisory council on social security also recommended friday 
continuing the payroll tax rate at the current level to build 
reserves as a cushion for the retirement of 75 million baby 
boomers which will begin around 2010 
the council said in its interim report that maintaining a strong 
social security system depends on having a healthy growing economy 
and that large deficits in the federal budget weaken the economy 
the council believes that the growing social security reserves 
should not routinely be used simply to offset large operating 
deficits in the rest of the federal budget the panel said 
the panels report said the financial soundness of the social 
security trust funds is not affected by whether the trust funds are 
included or excluded in calculating deficit reduction targets 
but taking social security out of the grammrudmanhollings 
calculations will help federal policymakers and the american 
people focus on the fundamental importance of reducing the deficit 
and moving toward a surplus in the overall federal budget the 
council said 
the council also opposed changing the social security programs 
financing to a payasyougo system in which payroll taxes 
would be set at a rate sufficient to raise enough revenues to cover 
current expenses and maintain a contingency reserve 
