richard secord and a cargo carrier once owned by 
the cia took pains to hide their involvement in the illegal supply 
of arms to the nicaraguan contras during the mid1980s according 
to testimony at a federal trial 
the family of william sawyer jr and eugene hasenfus sole 
survivor of a october 1986 crash in nicaragua claimed friday that 
secord and southern air transport misrepresented the supply mission 
and skimped on safety equipment 
sawyer died when the sandinistas shot down the c123 cargo plane 
as it ferried supplies to the usbacked rebels the incident 
helped unravel the irancontra affair 
in the trial of a federal damage lawsuit attorneys for hasenfus 
and the sawyer family are seeking a preliminary estimate of 34 
million including expenses caused by the crash and lost income 
secord a retired air force general who pleaded guilty to lying 
