to demand water 
water is a right and not a privilege many of their banners 
said 
the government says there is little it can do 
lima is in the middle of a desert and rain is rare most of the 
citys water comes from the rimac river which is fed by mountain 
streams and a drought in the southern andes has left the streams 
nearly dry 
according to the meteorological service the drought is caused 
by a change in the winds that usually bring moist sea air to the 
mountains 
decades of neglect of perus infrastructure make the situation 
worse not only has the water supply been cut in half the city 
water company said but 48 percent of that seeps into the ground or 
spills into the ocean through broken pipes 
other other basic services also have collapsed because of the 
drought 
limas power comes from five hydroelectric plants it is being 
rationed and the daily outages in turn affect the water companys 
ability to move water and operate wells 
reservoirs built to run the hydroelectric plants during the dry 
season now supply much of the capitals water 
an emergency welldigging program has helped but ground water 
levels are dropping rapidly 
the water company says many wells will go dry within a few 
months and the power company says its reservoirs hold only enough 
water to operate its plants until the next rainy season in 
november 
peru is poorly prepared to deal with the droughts effects it 
is in the grips of its worst economic crisis inflation exceeds 
3000 percent a year four of five people lack steady work and the 
government is bankrupt 
presidentelect alberto fujimori issued a plea for emergency 
food aid even before taking office saturday 
for now a few hundred water trucks must serve limas thirsty 
millions 
its not an easy job said santiago guttierez who is in 
charge of 100 trucks we have 250000 more people to bring water 
to than last year 
he pointed at a 30yearold ford its tank leaking from at least 
20 holes and added and we dont have the best equipment 
many residents of cruz de motupe complain about the men who 
drive the trucks 
they say the price is 35 cents for 20 gallons of water but the 
drivers often charge more the same amount of water delivered by 
pipe to an upperclass home costs a fraction of a cent 
we have no choice but to pay said rosalia diez who is 29 
and has four children at least my husband has a job some people 
just cant afford the water its really terrible 
yellow and red flowers bloom in front of the diez shack 
nourished by the family dishwater 
nelly gonzalez lives where the water trucks rarely go the 
plants in front of her house are dead she has seven children her 
husband makes shoes 
to have money and not to have water for the babies its 
absurd its tragic i hope the rains come soon because if they 
dont i think it means were not supposed to live 
