blackmun evolved into a moreoftenthannot liberal he wrote the 
roe vs wade decision that legalized abortion and once said with a 
sigh he supposed that was what theyd put on his gravestone 
white was nominated by president john f kennedy his close 
friend he pretty much has been a new frontiersman on civil 
rights said schwartz but on other issues he has trended away 
from the persuasion that got him his appointment 
mark tushnet a law professor at georgetown university 
dissented if we could ask john kennedy whether byron white has 
worked out as he expected i would guess the answer would be yes 
tushnet said 
stevens was appointed by president gerald r ford to take the 
seat of the foremost liberal william o douglas whom ford as a 
congressman had tried to have impeached stevens a court 
maverick has evolved into sharing the courts middletoliberal 
ground with blackmun 
oconnor is in the middletoconservative bloc with white she 
turned out to be much more of a centrist than reagans three other 
choices william rehnquist whom he elevated to chief justice and 
antonin scalia and anthony kennedy 
tushnet thinks justices surprise their nominating presidents 
only occasionally but lawrence marshall who teaches 
constitutional law at northwestern university said that in the 
past two or three decades a good third of appointees have 
disappointed their appointers with respect to major issues 
marshall has a theory presidents get surprised when they pick 
nominees on nonideological grounds 
when their agenda is ideology as it was when reagan picked 
scalia and rehnquist i think the surprises are a lot less 
frequent he said 
he cites oconnor and warren as examples reagan chose oconnor 
not for her ideology but because he had promised in his campaign to 
pick a woman eisenhower promised to name warren to the court at 
the republican convention in 1952 where warren then governor of 
california was competing with him for the presidential nomination 
there was something else going on other than an attempt by the 
president to choose ideologically said marshall 
what does that say about souters likelihood to surprise 
marshalls hunch is that bush deliberately did not scrutinize 
souter on ideological grounds opting for an unknown quantity and 
getting a nominee who on the court is capable of surprises 
