the second tropical storm of the atlantic hurricane 
season formed today off the florida coast with sustained winds near 
50 mph meteorologists said 
tropical storm bertha was nearly stationary early today but the 
national hurricane center in suburban coral gables predicted it 
would drift northward conditions also were favorable that it will 
pick up in strength by sunday the center reported 
at noon edt today bertha was located about 280 miles east of 
cape canaveral near latitude 287 north and longitude 756 west 
maximum sustained winds were near 50 mph 
on friday forecasters stopped issuing advisories concerning the 
remains of tropical storm arthur as the system was reduced to a 
tropical wave 
arthurs sustained winds dropped from 70 mph to 35 mph thursday 
briefly building to 40 mph again and then dropped below 39 mph for 
good thats the minimum wind speed for a tropical disturbance to 
be defined as a tropical storm 
storm watches for the southern coasts of puerto rico and the 
island of hispaniola shared by haiti and the dominican republic 
were lifted by thursday afternoon 
there were reports of heavy rain but no serious damage and 
injuries on the islands 
arthur the hurricane seasons first named storm began forming 
sunday in the open atlantic the season runs from june 1 to nov 30 
