<TEXT>
in the heart of asia far from the tumult of the 
kremlin a new mood of defiance and independence is taking hold 
this is the first installment of a fourpart series by an ap 
special correspondent who traveled through the restive soviet south 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
townsfolk in this ancient capital of 
tiled turquoise domes and haunting memories are starting to refer 
to the soviet state in the same past tense they apply to tamerlane 
and genghis khan 
the soviet union is rotting away said alex ulko a young 
painter and english student at the university of samarkand 
within a few years asians will be shaping their own nations 
moscow is omnipresent in soviet central asia from government 
offices and communist party headquarters to donkeyriding kgb 
informants in remote hamlets 
but new political currents rooted in an islamic religious 
revival economic resentment and environmental concerns are 
carrying asian peoples inexorably further from the kremlin 
although lenins ironcast goatee still juts resolutely forward 
in city parks asians revere their own wise men in flowing white 
beards and colored robes who evoke a past few have forgotten a 
past almost palpable at night when islamic chants can be heard down 
twisting lanes shaded by mulberries 
the five central asian republics kazakhstan turkmenistan 
uzbekistan tadzhikistan and kirghizia stretch from the caspian 
sea to china an area almost as big as the united states their 50 
million inhabitants 20 million in uzbekistan make up a fifth of 
the soviet population a few examine 21st century problems in 
nuclear physics and biochemistry but many more live in rag tents 
or mud hovels as in the days of the golden horde 
in some ways central asia is marked indelibly by a century of 
russian czars and commissars but many here see the russian 
interlude as destined to be yet another turn of history no more 
vital to the present than when camels plied the silk road from 
china to europe 
new political parties ecological movements moslem clergymen in 
reopened mosques and young radicals all press for broader freedoms 
leading to independence even local communist party cadres are 
insisting on greater home rule 
perestroika has brought truth but truth has brought unrest 
noted agzam rahmidov an english professor in this old crossroads 
city in uzbekistan 
for one thing central asians complain of economic exploitation 
the uzbekistan prime minister shukrulla mirsaidov contends his 
people pay out three times as much to the central government as 
they get back 
in june uzbekistan and tadzhikistan refused to export food to 
other republics at the low prices decreed by the state later the 
uzbek parliament adopted a preliminary declaration of 
sovereignty 
antimoscow sentiment reaches deep into daily life 
russian settlers are leaving the region at a quickening pace 
spurred by sporadic pogroms against ethnic minorities youths are 
evading the military draft and rebelling against officers they 
accuse of bias 
in a nation fraught with more immediate crises these pressures 
stew largely out of sight 
in june a border clash between uzbeks and kirghizis in the old 
holy city of osh commanded attention as the official death toll 
mounted to as high as 800 but when soviet troops imposed calm the 
spotlight moved on 
the situation in central asia is very serious and we dont 
understand it fully said igor krupnik a conflict specialist at 
the academy of sciences in moscow no one has the data 
the problem central asians say is that distant analysts are 
often thrown off by convenient generalities about peoples who are 
anything but homogeneous 
over millennia borders were traced across the sands by 
conquerors from the mongol hordes to turkish tyrants like 
tamerlane to the russian czars josef stalin drew the last map in 
the 1920s when the regions of turkestan and eastern bukhara were 
transformed into five republics 
the plains of kazakhstan biggest and northernmost of the five 
separate european russia from asia to the south lie the other 
four in the east the small mountainous enclaves of tadzhikistan 
and kirghizia bordering china and afghanistan in the west the 
highlands and deserts of uzbekistan and turkmenistan stretching 
toward the oilfields of the caspian sea 
these central asian neighbors are linked by the koran and often 
by common linguistic roots but just as often they are divided by 
disputes over land and water 
in the soviet grand plan the whole region was given over to 
cotton fields were irrigated from the majestic rivers amu darya 
and syr darya and russian migrants settled frontier lands today 
only 40 percent of the kazakhstan population is kazakh 
but decades of poor planning have so bled the rivers that they 
no longer replenish the aral sea half of the worlds fourth 
largest lake has dried up its exposed lakebed now just loose salt 
poisoned by pesticide runoff to revive the aral sea uzbeks want 
to cut off the karakum canal used by the turkmens to water their 
desert 
land was exploited in the most disgusting colonial way said 
sergei kapitsa of the physical problems institute in the soviet 
academy of sciences 
central asian planners want to diversify from cotton but the 
region is short of energy and the tadzhiks ensconced in high 
mountains balk at flooding villages for more hydroelectic dams 
in this climate of tension an isolated skirmish over a piece of 
scarce farmland like the one in osh can flash overnight into 
pitched battles in capital cities hundreds of miles apart 
explosive mixtures have resulted from past soviet policies of 
dispersing inconvenient minorities to onceremote areas such as 
the fergana valley which includes osh 
last year rampaging uzbeks killed at least 100 people in 
pogroms against turks resettled from georgia almost two generations 
ago other minorities including russians were also targeted 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP900728-0082 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
this february an estimated 50 people were killed in riots in 
the tadzhik capital dushanbe reportedly touched off by rumors 
that armenian refugees would settle there in may mobs burned 47 
homes of armenians and jews in the fergana valley 
authorities cite local causes for each outbreak sometimes 
blaming unnamed political opportunists religious fanatics or 
drugcrazed hooligans but others see deeper roots 
the problem is social frustration among a generation of youths 
who are losing their old values and see nothing to replace them 
said munira shadheedi a historian in dushanbe 
opposition politicians mostly writers and other intellectuals 
see a policy vacuum as communist party stalwarts push ahead with 
only modifications of ideas that have failed to inspire confidence 
these new leaders say it is too early to design specific 
programs for independence first most say they must abolish 
entrenched official corruption which impoverishes and embitters 
their populations 
alternative parties are beginning to attract wide support the 
uzbekistan popular front birlik has inspired similar movements in 
other republics krupnik said he saw signs these disparate 
opposition groups were linking up forging the beginnings of a 
grassroots movement across central asia 
their main obstacle is a historical aversion to mixing among 
ethnic groups in the region he said 
if central asia mixes anywhere it is here in samarkand a city 
of 390000 people that recently celebrated its 2500th anniversary 
the old mud synagogue blends unnoticed into a block of moslem 
houses men of all religions wear the same square black skullcaps 
embroidered in white a multitude of nationalities sits together 
for tea and patterned wheels of bread escaping the sun under shade 
trees 
but a chat with samarkand university students suggests that this 
harmony of old is changing fast 
a crimean tatar woman felt growing antipathy and said her family 
wanted badly to get home her russianukrainian friend said uzbeks 
are making up for lost time in reasserting national pride 
there is a very dark fear which is difficult to understand 
concluded a young russian like the others reluctant to be quoted 
by name we see discrimination against others the russians are 
next 
