reported the car he had rented and returned as stolen 
a broward county circuit court jury awarded dania businessman 
michael mancusi 300000 in compensatory damages and 27 million 
in punitive damages friday for malicious prosecution 
the night i was standing in jail i knew it was wrong 
mancusi said saturday big corporations like this should not be 
able to swoop down and sweep people off the streets and put them in 
jail 
the case began when mancusi rented an oldsmobile calais from the 
fort lauderdalebased company for a week on july 15 1986 he kept 
the car longer but didnt think there would be a problem because he 
had rented cars from alamo before on a monthtomonth basis 
he said he received a letter demanding the cars return three 
weeks later and a company employee agreed to an extension over the 
telephone 
but mancusi said he was called by a police detective aug 27 and 
told the car had been listed on a hot sheet of stolen cars 
he said he returned the car that same day 
but on sept 2 an alamo employee signed an autotheft arrest 
affidavit and mancusi was taken to jail 14 days later 
during booking mancusis name was spelled incorrectly on jail 
records leaving him in limbo behind bars when relatives tried to 
bail him out because there was no record of him under the correct 
spelling 
