<TEXT>
states should move away from the arbitrary 
grouping of students by age governors said saturday in a report 
that criticizes assembly line teaching 
the recommendation is one of several in the report being offered 
at the national governors associations annual meeting in mobile 
ala the report outlines the strategy for meeting the educational 
goals endorsed by president bush and the governors in late february 
the strategy was developed by the nga task force on education 
cochaired by govs bill clinton of arkansas and carroll campbell 
of south carolina 
despite all the effort that has been made in the decade of the 
80s to invest more money start new programs and raise standards 
we still face a crisis clinton said in mobile ala where the 
governors gathered to open their annual conference 
we are still a long way from meeting these goals we still 
havent made fundamental and dramatic changes in the very design 
and structure of the education system clinton said 
but we first have to face the fact that we still have problems 
with the attitudes of the citizens whose votes and opinions 
will determine whether we can make the changes we must make 
the proposals will be discussed this week at the governors 
plenary session 
the task force report criticized elementary and secondary 
schools for assigning students based on where they live grouping 
them according to age and narrowly defined ability and offering 
them curriculum and textbooks that are fragmented and 
repetitive 
the present system requires too many teachers who focus 
largely on the mastery of discrete lowlevel skills and isolated 
facts the report said by doing so the report says the system 
denies opportunities for students to master subject matter in 
depth learn more complex problemsolving skills or apply the 
skills they do learn 
this arrangement was designed to prepare a work force destined 
for the assembly lines of the industrial age the report says 
the task force suggested that states rely on practices that 
expand rather than limit access to learning opportunities for 
lowachieving students said the report 
the report noted that age grading and fixed school years 
could be detrimental to those preschool and younger children not 
making adequate progress 
states should consider other approaches such as upgraded early 
primary programs multiage grouping or summer programs that allow 
children to progress at their own rate and still meet performance 
standards said the report 
other specific recommendations include placing top priority on 
developing new tools for assessing student performance 
the governors report said that portfolios essays or other 
openended problems that require students to synthesize integrate 
and apply knowledge and data need to be developed as alternatives 
to the exclusive use of conventional multiplechoice tests 
the task force also asked states to conduct a statewide literacy 
assessment and asked employers to audit the literacy and other 
skills of their own employees 
shirley mcbay president of the quality education for minorities 
network praised the strategies and underscored the governors 
recommendation to eliminate tracking and ability grouping 
they have recognized as did we that nothing short of 
restructuring the nations educational system will do and that a 
holistic coordinated approach is required said mcbay 
the national education association a few weeks earlier called 
for elimination of academic tracking stressing that the practice 
keeps underachievers down and lumps minorities into classes that 
can prevent them from realizing their potential 
the american federation of teachers however complained the 
strategies fail to specify the role the federal government should 
be playing in assisting the states 
</TEXT>
