<TEXT>
voters on foot and horseback flocked 
to the polls sunday to vote in this sovietbloc countrys first 
multiparty elections that will decide the pace of democratic and 
freemarket reforms 
at high school no 1 in ulan bator election officials showed 
observers from various parties that the ballot boxes were empty 
when voting began they then used string and sealing wax to secure 
the boxes 
voters most wearing the traditional mongolian herders dress 
began arriving just after the polls opened at 7 am 
from the start it is going quite well said amarbayasgolam 
an observer from the mongolian democratic party the largest 
opposition party two british election observers also were on hand 
among 19 from various countries 
five new parties are challenging the ruling communists formally 
known as the mongolian peoples revolutionary party in the 
elections for the national provincial and local legislatures 
the communists who have held power in this remote central asian 
nation since 1921 are assured control of the national legislature 
the 430seat great peoples hural after winning a primary election 
july 22 the opposition parties only have 130 candidates still in 
the running out of an original 338 
but the opposition hopes to win in the new 53seat small hural 
which will meet between the great hurals annual sessions and have 
considerable power its seats will be allocated to parties 
according to the results of a party preference poll that is 
included on sundays ballot 
at stake are the speed and boldness of political and economic 
reforms which street demonstrations last winter and spring forced 
the communists to accept 
by agreeing to free elections the ruling party added mongolia 
to the list of sovietbloc nations experimenting with democracy 
though the reform movement has swept through eastern europe 
mongolia is the first asian communist state to hold multiparty 
elections 
however the opposition has accused the communists of only 
paying lipservice to reform in order to stay in power they and 
ordinary mongolians also have complained that the election is not 
fair because greater weight is given to rural votes expected to 
favor the communists they also complain that nominations were made 
before all the parties were able to register 
in the election district where high school no 1 is located 
however the mongolian democratic partys candidate a 31yearold 
rock star is favored to win a great hural seat tsogtsaikhan a 
singer and guitarist for the group honkh finished first in the 
primary in that district 
chultemtsuren a 75yearold retired official who wore world war 
ii medals said he voted for the rock star asked why he didnt 
vote for the communist candidate he said i worry about the 
future of the country thats why i vote for a younger man 
chultemtsuren like most mongolians uses only one name 
