saturday as candidates made the rounds nationwide in a final effort 
to get out the vote 
more than 4000 youths rallied in the evening in front of the 
lenin museum in ulan bator to cheer candidates for the mongolian 
democratic party and listen to honkh and other rock groups 
i am a permanent fighter for democracy declared dorligjav 
the partys deputy chairman we will fight not only for the 
election but beyond for political change 
the crowd waved the partys blue banners and joined in singing 
honkhs biggest hit a song that urges mongolians to wake up 
the sound of the bell 
in one shantytown district in western ulan bator an elderly 
buddhist monk who is running for the great hural led residents in 
dedicating a hilltop shrine saturday afternoon they erected a 
stone carved with the picture of a goddess and placed gifts of 
yogurt and candy before it 
local residents said the hill had been an informal place of 
prayer before the communists virtually banned worship in the 1930s 
religious freedom was one of the demands of the prodemocracy 
demonstrators and believers have begun reopening temples on their 
own in the past few months 
as the group dispersed a campaign worker called out vote for 
the national progressives the party to which the monk dagva 
belongs 
the national progressives also have a candidate in one of the 
elections most dramatic races one of their founding members a 
29yearold lawyer named ganbold is facing the chairman of the 
communist party gombojavyn ochirbat in a race for the great hural 
ochirbat 61 took office in march after the demonstrations 
forced his predecessor jambyn batmonh to resign he has embraced 
reform but also stresses moderation and maintaining order the 
national progressives favor rapid privatization and establishment 
of laws to guarantee freedoms 
ganbolds campaign workers handed out the candidates platform 
and pictures of genghis khan the 13thcentury warrior who built a 
great mongol empire 
