<TEXT>
a remotecontrolled submarine searching the 
ocean floor for the cargo door that blew off a united airlines jet 
last year has yet to find anything after four days underwater a 
navy spokesman said friday 
the orion deep submergence system equipped with sonar and a 
video camera is prowling the ocean bottom nearly three miles deep 
and about 100 miles south of honolulu 
the search will cover 24 square miles of the ocean floor twice 
and is expected to continue until the middle of next week lt 
cmdr bob anderson said 
in the feb 24 1989 accident the cargo door on united airlines 
flight 811 opened at 22000 feet tearing away a section of the 
boeing 747 fuselage of the 355 passengers aboard the flight from 
honolulu international airport to new zealand nine were swept to 
their deaths and five were seriously injured 
the crew managed to return the jet safely to honolulu 
the national transportation safety board has completed its 
inquiry into the accident but requested the search for the 10 
footby10 foot door with hopes its inspection will lead to better 
plane safety 
personnel aboard the 226foot navy ocean tug narragansett have 
placed in the ocean a field of electronic transponders which 
transmit electrical signals to chart movements of the video 
cameraequipped orion sub 
the transponders hang about 150 feet above the ocean floor 
around the perimeter of the search area 
if the door is spotted by the submersible a second device will 
be deployed at a later date to recover it 
the door is believed to be lying under about 15000 feet of 
water 
the ntsbs inquiry determined that a faulty design of the doors 
locking mechanism probably caused a cockpit panel light to falsely 
indicate the door was locked 
it blamed united boeing co and the federal aviation 
administration for failure to correct problems with the door 
